1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,120
Hello and welcome to In Simple Terms with Satish.

2
00:00:03,120 --> 00:00:07,960
Today, let's understand how chiplets make modern AI chips possible.

3
00:00:07,960 --> 00:00:13,360
Once you understand that a chip is a manufactured circuit on silicon, the next question is obvious.

4
00:00:13,360 --> 00:00:16,300
Why not just make one giant chip for AI?

5
00:00:16,300 --> 00:00:18,080
One huge chip sounds simple.

6
00:00:18,080 --> 00:00:23,800
More transistors, more compute, more memory, more power, but chip manufacturing punishes

7
00:00:23,800 --> 00:00:24,800
size.

8
00:00:24,800 --> 00:00:30,000
A large die is harder to make, harder to test, harder to cool, and more likely to be

9
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:31,920
ruined by a tiny defect.

10
00:00:31,920 --> 00:00:37,040
There is also a manufacturing limit called a reticle limit, which is basically the maximum

11
00:00:37,040 --> 00:00:41,040
area that can be exposed as one pattern during lithography.

12
00:00:41,040 --> 00:00:45,160
So the engineering problem is not, can we dream of a bigger AI chip?

13
00:00:45,160 --> 00:00:49,680
The problem is, can we build something that behaves like a bigger chip without depending

14
00:00:49,680 --> 00:00:52,280
on one impossible piece of silicon?

15
00:00:52,280 --> 00:00:53,960
That is where chiplets come in.

16
00:00:53,960 --> 00:00:59,720
A chiplet is a smaller piece of silicon designed to do a specific job, then combined with other

17
00:00:59,720 --> 00:01:02,040
pieces inside one package.

18
00:01:02,040 --> 00:01:08,200
Instead of one giant monolithic die, engineers assemble multiple dies very close together.

19
00:01:08,200 --> 00:01:13,280
One chiplet may focus on compute, another may handle input and output, another may connect

20
00:01:13,280 --> 00:01:14,280
to memory.

21
00:01:14,280 --> 00:01:18,680
Together they are packaged, so the final product feels like one accelerator.

22
00:01:18,680 --> 00:01:20,520
This is the important shift.

23
00:01:20,520 --> 00:01:25,760
Silicon AI chips are becoming packaged systems, not just single pieces of silicon.

24
00:01:25,760 --> 00:01:29,240
NVIDIA's Blackwell architecture is a useful example.

25
00:01:29,240 --> 00:01:36,360
NVIDIA says Blackwell GPUs have 208 billion transistors and use two reticle-limited dies

26
00:01:36,360 --> 00:01:40,600
connected by a 10 terabytes per second chip-to-chip interconnect.

27
00:01:40,600 --> 00:01:43,400
So they behave as one unified GPU.

28
00:01:43,400 --> 00:01:45,820
That line is the whole story in miniature.

29
00:01:45,820 --> 00:01:48,840
The product wants to act like one massive chip.

30
00:01:48,840 --> 00:01:53,880
The engineering underneath uses multiple pieces and an extremely fast connection.

31
00:01:53,880 --> 00:01:57,160
The second reason chiplets matter is specialization.

32
00:01:57,160 --> 00:02:01,760
Not every part of an accelerator benefits from the same manufacturing process.

33
00:02:01,760 --> 00:02:05,220
The fastest logic may need the most advanced node.

34
00:02:05,220 --> 00:02:11,120
But input-output circuits, memory controllers, cache, or analog functions may work better,

35
00:02:11,120 --> 00:02:14,480
cheaper, or more reliably on a different node.

36
00:02:14,480 --> 00:02:19,600
Chiplets let designers mix optimized parts instead of forcing every function into one

37
00:02:19,600 --> 00:02:20,600
process.

38
00:02:20,600 --> 00:02:22,000
The third reason is memory.

39
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:25,220
AI accelerators do not only need arithmetic.

40
00:02:25,220 --> 00:02:29,880
They need to move huge amounts of data to the compute units without starving them.

41
00:02:29,880 --> 00:02:38,400
AMD's MI300X, for example, lists 192 gb of HBM3 memory and 5.3 terabytes per second of

42
00:02:38,400 --> 00:02:40,000
peak memory bandwidth.

43
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:42,460
Those numbers are not just impressive specs.

44
00:02:42,460 --> 00:02:47,580
They show that memory capacity and bandwidth are part of the AI chip architecture.

45
00:02:47,580 --> 00:02:51,340
This is why advanced packaging has become so important.

46
00:02:51,340 --> 00:02:55,500
Packaging used to sound like the boring final wrapper around a finished chip.

47
00:02:55,500 --> 00:02:58,220
Now, packaging is part of the design itself.

48
00:02:58,220 --> 00:03:02,860
The package has to place chiplets and high bandwidth memory close enough that signals

49
00:03:02,860 --> 00:03:07,160
move quickly, with less power, less delay, and enough bandwidth.

50
00:03:07,160 --> 00:03:11,300
If those connections are too slow, the chiplets become separate islands.

51
00:03:11,300 --> 00:03:15,100
If the connections are fast enough, they can act like one system.

52
00:03:15,100 --> 00:03:17,780
That is why standards such as UCIE matter.

53
00:03:17,780 --> 00:03:20,940
UCIE is an open chiplet interconnect standard.

54
00:03:20,940 --> 00:03:26,900
Its goal is to define how chiplets talk inside a package, including the physical layer, protocols,

55
00:03:26,900 --> 00:03:29,300
software model, and compliance testing.

56
00:03:29,300 --> 00:03:34,140
The long-term dream is a healthier chiplet ecosystem, where pieces can be mixed more

57
00:03:34,140 --> 00:03:38,680
easily instead of every company building only closed one-off links.

58
00:03:38,680 --> 00:03:40,700
But there are real trade-offs.

59
00:03:40,700 --> 00:03:42,620
Trade-offs are not free magic.

60
00:03:42,620 --> 00:03:48,020
Engineers still have to manage signal integrity, heat, power delivery, testing, reliability,

61
00:03:48,020 --> 00:03:52,180
security, and software behavior across multiple pieces of silicon.

62
00:03:52,180 --> 00:03:57,500
The system may be modular inside, but it must behave like one reliable machine outside.

63
00:03:57,500 --> 00:04:00,480
For software engineers, the lesson is useful.

64
00:04:00,480 --> 00:04:04,100
Hardware architecture is becoming more like distributed systems.

65
00:04:04,100 --> 00:04:09,820
Even inside one accelerator, performance depends on data movement, memory locality, interconnect

66
00:04:09,820 --> 00:04:12,060
bandwidth, and where work is placed.

67
00:04:12,060 --> 00:04:13,780
The clear takeaway is this.

68
00:04:13,780 --> 00:04:17,580
Modern AI chips are not only about smaller transistors.

69
00:04:17,580 --> 00:04:19,140
They are about system design.

70
00:04:19,140 --> 00:04:24,500
In simple terms, chiplets let engineers build larger, more specialized, more memory-rich

71
00:04:24,500 --> 00:04:30,360
accelerators by assembling multiple silicon blocks inside one advanced package and making

72
00:04:30,360 --> 00:04:32,780
them behave as one fast machine.

73
00:04:32,780 --> 00:04:34,540
The magic is not one block.

74
00:04:34,540 --> 00:04:36,040
The magic is the connection.

75
00:04:36,040 --> 00:04:40,720
If this helped you understand the topic in simple terms, follow or subscribe to In Simple

76
00:04:40,720 --> 00:04:45,120
Terms with Satish and share this episode with one friend who likes technology.

77
00:04:45,120 --> 00:04:46,960
I will see you in the next episode.
